   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Harvard_604756_1847-01_page01.jpg"/>
            <opener>
               <dateline>
                  <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Edgeworthstown_IE">Edgeworths Town</placeName>
                  <lb/>
                  <date when="1847-01-14">
                     <choice>
                        <orig>Jan<hi rend="superscript">y</hi>.</orig>
                        <reg>January</reg>
                     </choice> 14<hi rend="superscript">h</hi>. 1847</date>
               </dateline>
               <lb/>
               <salute>
                  Dear Sir,<lb/>
               </salute>
            </opener>
            <p>Your letter dated New Years<lb/>
               day - <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Riedenburg_GW">Riedenburg</placeName> Lue de <choice>
                  <orig>Con-<lb/>
                  stance</orig>
                  <reg>Constance</reg>
               </choice> reached me three<lb/>
               days ago - It gave me as<lb/>
               both your former letters<lb/>
               did sincere pleasure from<lb/>
               the persuasion that the<lb/>
               kind and partial feelings<lb/>
               which you express for my<lb/>
               self and my writings are<lb/>
               however flattering not<lb/>
               flattery - as they come I<lb/>
               believe most truly from<lb/>
               your warm heart and<lb/>
               enthusiastic gratitude<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>Gratitude far above my<lb/>
               deserth - but no matter for that<lb/>
               - It is I own delightful to me<lb/>
               even to fancy that I can be of<lb/>
               use and pleasure to a man<lb/>
               <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Harvard_604756_1847-01_page02.jpg"/>
               
               genius and <add>that</add> I may hope to<lb/>
               encourage his exertions and<lb/>
               perhaps assist from my old<lb/>
               Experience <del>in</del>
               <lb/>
            </p>
            <p>In the first place then to<lb/>
               answer your concluding &amp;<lb/>
               most important question; I<lb/>
               will do my best to give you<lb/>
               any assistance in my power<lb/>
               in judging of the sketch of the<lb/>
               new story you are planning<lb/>
               -&amp; which you do me the honor<lb/>
               to say you wish me to see -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>I need not I trust say that it<lb/>
               shall be secret and safe with<lb/>
               me- - But I must beg that it<lb/>
               may be exactly what you<lb/>
               describe - a sketch - I <hi rend="underline">cannot </hi>
               <lb/>
               look over a manuscript - not only<lb/>
               because I have not time literally<lb/>
               But because I have made it<lb/>
               a rule from which I have never<lb/>
                  deviated <add>
                  <hi rend="underline">never</hi> to look over any <choice>
                     <abbr>M<hi rend="superscript">n</hi>.</abbr>
                     <reg>manuscript</reg>
                  </choice> for the press</add> even where much pressed<lb/>
               by near connexions, <del>to look over </del>
               <lb/>
               <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Harvard_604756_1847-01_page03.jpg"/>
               
               Do not send me the <hi rend="underline">sketch</hi> even<lb/>
               if you have written the story<lb/>
               - You must give me the assurance<lb/>
               that you have not written it<lb/>
               otherwise I could not be of any<lb/>
               use - for I could not bring my<lb/>
               self to suggest different courses<lb/>
               or alterations of your course<lb/>
               if your road was already taken<lb/>
               or even decided upon -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>My present frankness tho<lb/>
               it may strike you at this <choice>
                  <orig>mo-<lb/>
                  ment</orig>
                  <reg>moment</reg>
               </choice> as rather uncourteous<lb/>
               may save us both <choice>
                  <orig>disappoint<lb/>
                  -ment</orig>
                  <reg>disappointment</reg>
               </choice> or useless pain hereafter<lb/>
                  - I <choice>
                  <abbr>sh<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>
                  </abbr>
                  <reg>should</reg>
               </choice> not be so presumptuous<lb/>
               as to my power to assist you<lb/>
               in looking over a <hi rend="underline">sketch</hi>
               <lb/>
               had I not had for many<lb/>
               many years (I being now 80)<lb/>
               the practice of <hi rend="underline">making</hi> &amp; <choice>
                  <orig>
                     <hi rend="underline">alter</hi>
                     <lb/>
                  ing</orig>
                  <reg>altering</reg>
               </choice> sketches of <add>my own</add> stories <choice>
                  <orig>accord-<lb/>
                     ing</orig>
                  <reg>according</reg>
               </choice> to the suggestions &amp; advice<lb/>
                  of my <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeR1">father</persName> -<lb/>
               you know "Experience doth attain"<lb/>
               &amp;c<lb/>
            </p>
            <pb n="4" facs="Edgeworth_Harvard_604756_1847-01_page04.jpg"/>
            <p>I augur well of your Tales of<lb/>
                  the <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Tyrol_AT">Tyrol</placeName> - from Nature and<lb/>
               Life - new to us - At least new<lb/>
               enough for your genius to<lb/>
               make advantage of the <choice>
                  <orig>pictu<lb/>
                  -resque</orig>
                  <reg>picturesque</reg>
               </choice> and the <hi rend="underline">graphic</hi> -<lb/>
               whether comic or tragic <del>
                  <unclear/>
               </del>
               <lb/>
               Be pleased to keep a good <choice>
                  <orig>pro-<lb/>
                  portion</orig>
                  <reg>proportion</reg>
               </choice> of <hi rend="underline">comic</hi> - I conceive<lb/>
               that your Publisher would agree<lb/>
               with me in this advice -<lb/>
                  "Courage <persName ref="./Personography.xml#Molie1">Moliere</persName>! voila de<lb/>
               la bonne comedie!<lb/>
               was called out from the pitt<lb/>
               you remember - All can laugh<lb/>
               - Few can think - And the<lb/>
               few who do are glad to be<lb/>
               relieved from the effort often<lb/>
               by a good laugh - The laugh<lb/>
               on your side - you win<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>Recollect <persName ref="./Personography.xml#MoorX2">Dr Moore</persName> who went<lb/>
               to the Italian Theatre Buffo <choice>
                  <orig>resolv-<lb/>
                     <unclear>ing</unclear>
                  </orig>
                  <reg>resolving</reg>
               </choice> he would not be made to laugh<lb/>
               - But he was made to laugh &amp;<lb/>
               was thankful for it - &amp; could not<lb/>
               criticise - or if he had nobody w<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> have<lb/>
               minded<lb/>
            </p>
            <pb n="5" facs="Edgeworth_Harvard_604756_1847-01_page05.jpg"/>
            <p>I received a letter<lb/>
                  from you dated <date when="1846-07-16">16<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>. July 46</date>
               <lb/>
                  which I answered the <date when="1846-07-31">31<hi rend="superscript">t</hi>. of that<lb/>
               month</date>, in which I told you that<lb/>
                  I had seen the <title ref="./Workography.xml#Knight1">Knight of <unclear>Gwynne</unclear>
               </title>
               <lb/>
               and all I thought about it &amp;<lb/>
               of the extreme difficulty of<lb/>
               getting all the parties out of their<lb/>
               difficulties -<lb/>
                  I have since received 4 <choice>
                  <abbr>
                     <add>
                        <unclear>vol.</unclear>
                     </add>
                  </abbr>
                  <reg>volume</reg>
               </choice>
               <unclear>numbers</unclear>
               <lb/>
                  of the <title ref="./Workography.xml#Knight1">Knight</title> -<lb/>
                  With the last <add>for <date when="1847-01">
                     <choice>
                        <abbr>Jan<hi rend="superscript">y</hi>
                        </abbr>
                        <reg>January</reg>
                     </choice> 47</date>,</add> which we finished<lb/>
               last night we are all delighted<lb/>
               - And I have the greatest <choice>
                  <orig>satis-<lb/>
                  faction</orig>
                  <reg>satisfaction</reg>
               </choice> in writing to tell you<lb/>
               so - and that my fears of<lb/>
               your never getting your people<lb/>
               out of their difficulties are<lb/>
               dispelled. I see light cheering<lb/>
               and brilliant -<lb/>
               <title ref="./Workography.xml#Knight1">O Halloran's speech on the trial</title>
               <lb/>
               is admirable - in the highest<lb/>
               style of eloquence - And with<lb/>
               the rare excellence in Irish<lb/>
               <pb n="6" facs="Edgeworth_Harvard_604756_1847-01_page06.jpg"/>
               
               or at least to shew that you<lb/>
               do not mean to pass it over -<lb/>
               <del>n</del>or to give a perfume to <choice>
                  <orig>conta-<lb/>
                  -gious</orig>
                  <reg>contagious</reg>
               </choice> matter -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               <title ref="./Workography.xml#Knight1">Your ladies are really<lb/>
               well bred - high bred and<lb/>
               high minded - So is the Knight<lb/>
               himself - <del>And</del> Daly is <choice>
                     <orig>incom-<lb/>
                  parably</orig>
                     <reg>incomparably</reg>
                  </choice> reckless - And <choice>
                     <orig>Demp<lb/>
                     sey</orig>
                     <reg>Dempsey</reg>
                  </choice> incomparably vulgar with<lb/>
               the true care &amp; bravado of his kind</title>
               <lb/>
               - Your characters are well<lb/>
               sustained and contrasted<lb/>
               strongly, through out the<lb/>
               whole of this last piece - And<lb/>
               without any affectation of<lb/>
               contrast or straining for effect,<lb/>
               - We long to see your next<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>There are two little books<lb/>
                  which have lately come in my way<lb/>
                  wh<hi rend="superscript">h</hi> I think you might like to look over<lb/>
                  - as they open views of what you might<lb/>
                  turn to new compositions (I have not expressed<lb/>
                  what I mean but yet I think you will<lb/>
                  give a guess at my meaning) <unclear>The books</unclear>
               <lb/>
                  are little or nothing in themselves<lb/>
               <pb n="7" facs="Edgeworth_Harvard_604756_1847-01_page07.jpg"/>
               
               except the life of a <hi rend="underline">child</hi> painter in one<lb/>
                  of these books - which is excellent -<lb/>
                  accompanied by drawings illustrative<lb/>
                  of the childs progress -<lb/>
               <del>The Title of</del> The book in which this story<lb/>
                  is to be found is called -<lb/>
               <title ref="./Workography.xml#Sketch1">"Flemish Tales"</title> - <choice>
                  <abbr>duod<hi rend="superscript">o</hi>.</abbr>
                  <reg>duodecimo</reg>
               </choice> price 4/6<lb/>
                  The other book is<lb/>
                     No. 39 of <persName ref="./Personography.xml#MurrJ3">Murray</persName>s Colonial Library<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#FordR1">Ford</persName>s <title ref="./Workography.xml#Gather1">
                  <unclear>vent</unclear> in Spain</title>
               <lb/>
                  Look for the description of<lb/>
                  Baking and Thrashing page - 115<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>I merely mark this as Graphic<lb/>
                  - and the sort that you could<lb/>
                  make something of -<lb/>
            </p>
            <closer>
               I am Dear Sir<lb/>
               very truly yours<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria Edgeworth</persName>
               <lb/>
            </closer>
            <postscript>
               <p>I am surprised and delighted<lb/>
                  by your having remembered<lb/>
                  <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeR1">my father</persName>s epigram so long<lb/>
               &amp; recollecting it so opportunely<lb/>
               to send it to "everlasting fame"</p>
               <lb/>
               <p>Never mind your publisher<lb/>
               Follow your own Genius &amp; he &amp; the<lb/>
               public will follow you<lb/>
               Fame never follow those who court her<lb/>
               among those who commend her</p>
               <lb/>
            </postscript>
         </div>
      </body>
